A Model of Representativity with Changing Beliefs¶

Groups of people often choose representatives to decide issues on their behalf. While a representative ideally stays aligned with the beliefs of their constituents throughout their tenure, group beliefs may change more quickly than representatives are selected; creating a potential for misrepresentation that we call representative drift. For example, a scientist committed to a particular theory may be chosen to serve as a program officer, allocating funds, and remain loyal to their theory while the field moves on. An employee may be chosen to advocate for their colleagues when choosing an insurance plan for their company, but become convinced by management to diverge from what their colleagues believe is the best plan. Or, a homeowner may be chosen to represent their neighborhood in a public council on solar panel regulations, but eventually drift to choose regulations that benefit a subset of neighbors at the expense of all others. Representative drift abounds. To gain intuition about the tendency of a group to become misrepresented over time, we developed a simple computational model from a few motivating assumptions:

  1. Group members live in a static social network.
  2. Representatives are chosen from the members of the group.
  3. The group changes beliefs more quickly than they choose representatives
  4. Members endogenously update their beliefs over time as a function of the average beliefs of a reference group.

Model Specifications¶

Most empirical social networks exhibit fat-tailed degree distributions and higher clustering than would randomly emerge. We consider three generative models that each capture these empirical properties to different extents. The Barabási-Albert (scale-free) model reproduces empirical degree distributions but not clustering [1]. The Watts-Strogatz (small world) model and its variants reproduce empirically observed clustering with a approximately uniform degree distribution [2,3]; and Holme-Kim (scale-free with tunable clustering) captures both [4]. Each of these models is used to generate a range of networks with varying size, clustering and degrees. To represent beliefs we generate a multivariate normal distribution with 10 features from a random symmetric positive semidefinite matrix, and randomly selected means bounded between 1 and 10. We consider two ways of choosing representatives: according to their status in the network (eigenvector centrality [5]), or their euclidean distance of their individual belief vector to the mean belief vector of the group. A representative is chosen at the beginning of each simulated world, and is never changed. As time advances, members of the group—representative included—update their beliefs based on the average beliefs of their first-order neighbors in the network, or their higher status neighbors depending on the model run [6]. Beliefs in any of the possible specifications described abo by belve, tend to stabilize fast and so we run each simulation for 10 steps. At each time step, we evaluate representative drift by calculating the euclidean distance between the current beliefs of the chosen representative, and the current mean beliefs of the group.

Results¶

Many social influence processes depend on the size and structure of ones social network [7] and so it is natural to expect to see such effects on representative drift. To test this prediction, we varied network size from 100-500-1000 nodes, holding the degree and clustering parameters constant. Across all network models and scales, selecting representatives by beliefs leads to representation that is about 1.75 times worse than members experience immediately after selecting a representative, and selecting by status leads to a roughly 2-2.25 fold decrease in representativity. Our results suggest that the influence of scale is minimal however.

Ashamed by our inability to find meaningful scaling behavior, we began to investigate whether the nature of social influence affects representative drift. As the peer effect increases in strength, the rate of representative drift increases, but if the network lacks isolates, the extent of representative drift if we ran the model forever would be identical regardless of the peer effect's strength. This suggests that longer representative tenures might be tolerable when communication is infrequent or influence is weak amongst the members of a group. If members only update beliefs based on their higher status peers, the difference between representatives selecting on highest status versus beliefs shrinks slightly. Here, the difference between network models increases in importance. With a scale-free degree distribution, the highest eigenvector centrality member will be connected directly to a high proportion of the nodes in a network, and other members will converge towards their beliefs. In the Newman-Watts network, selecting the highest status member is particularly bad, because they have relatively little direct influence on the beliefs of others, resulting in greater representative drift.

Future Directions¶

We showed above that our model can generate straightforward insights about representative drift, although our analysis has been limited and none of our results is particularly surprising. In addition to considering a wider range of parameter combinations, there are several ways to extend this work. First, representation and social influence may vary across different sectors of the economy. We may similarly expect to see cross-cultural variation, for example between individualistic and collectivistic nations. In individualistic societies, agents tend to select representatives based on individual opinions and personal relationships, whereas, in collectivistic societies, representatives may be self-appointed or chosen for their high-status within the group. Adding sectoral and cultural nuance to our model should therefore help us produce better policy recommendations. While we considered the effect of endogenously changing beliefs on representative drift, we omitted exogenous factors such as the effect of media, or heterogeneous shocks to members' beliefs. In addition, our evaluation of representative drift is fairly naive. It is not differences in beliefs that matter most, but the decisions that emerge from those differences which ultimately affect the lives of group members. We could address this by having representatives select from an exogenously provided set of policies, and by considering different forms of compliance. For example, members could opt out of policies chosen by their representative that they feel are particularly bad, which under some conditions would increase the marginal benefits of the compliance for those who prefer the chosen policy. Another unexplored part of our model is the effect of group diversity on representative drift under different conditions. We initially considered representing beliefs as a random draw from a multinomial distribution, which allows for straightforward tuning of group diversity via the distribution's entropy: $H \approx \frac{k-1}{2} \log_2 (2 \pi n e) + \frac{1}{2} \sum_{i=1} k \log_2 p_i$ where k is the number of possible outcomes, n is the number of trials, p is the probability of each outcome. But this approach makes a less realistic assumption about the structure of beliefs, and so some may prefer to directly manipulate the covariance matrix used to generate the multivariate normal distribution we actually use, to change the spread of beliefs in the population. Similarly, we kept a static network to simplify our model, but this is certainly not what empirical networks look like, and incorporating structural change, growth and exit from the group could lead to interesting results. The most important question is ultimately how we can reduce drift or mitigate the impact of a chosen representative when quick reselection is impractical. This could be accomplished through incentives, by manipulating the network to control how beliefs change, or through more complex strategies for selecting representatives.
